    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-03-03T19:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-03-03T19:00:00-05:00" n="189"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d189">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">711.00111 Armament Control/777a: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bingham</hi>
                    </persName>)<note n="34" xml:id="d189fn34">The same, March 3, 7 p.m., to the
                        Minister Resident in Ethiopia. Repeated as circular to Paris, Rome, Bern,
                        and Geneva.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-03-03T19:00:00-05:00"
                            >March 3, 1936—7 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>The President on February 29 signed the new Neutrality Act. At the same time he
                    issued a new Arms Embargo Proclamation<note n="35" xml:id="d189fn35">49 Stat.
                        3498.</note> revising in some minor details the enumeration of arms in his
                    former Proclamation of October 5.<note n="36" xml:id="d189fn36">49 Stat.
                        3474.</note> It was not necessary for him to issue a new proclamation in
                    regard to travel on belligerent ships as the Proclamation of October 5 on that
                        subject<note n="37" xml:id="d189fn37">49 Stat. 3476.</note> still stands.
                    When he signed the Act, he issued a statement<note n="38" xml:id="d189fn38"
                        >Department of State, <hi rend="italic">Press Releases</hi>, March 7, 1936,
                        p. 197.</note> in regard to the policy of this Government concerning
                    commercial transactions with the belligerents. In that statement, he said in
                    part: “The policies announced by the Secretary of State and myself at the time
                    of and subsequent to the issuance of the original proclamation will be
                    maintained in effect.” (See Radio Bulletin No. 50 of February 29).</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
